'''Maltos-Cannabis''' was a Swedish [[hemp seed]]-based malt beverage "food remedy" with sedative qualities produced beginning around the late 19th century into the early 20th century.<ref name="Small2016">{{cite book|author=Ernest Small|title=Cannabis: A Complete Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oo2KDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT228|date=14 October 2016|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-315-35059-2|pages=228–}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Eugene F. Starke|author2=Wilson A. Smith|author3=Wesley A. Dunn|title=The Medical Current|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ErRXAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA502|year=1895|publisher=Dunn & Smith|pages=502–}}</ref> The product was widely available in Sweden, Denmark, and Norway,<ref name="Decorte2016">{{cite book|author=Tom Decorte|title=World Wide Weed: Global Trends in Cannabis Cultivation and its Control|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Dv6NCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT53|date=11 February 2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-78521-6|pages=53–}}</ref> and was advertised and reviewed in American publications. An 1899 pharmaceutical reference book printed in Philadelphia defined the product: "A Swedish nutrient in form of a yellowish-white powder, possessing a taste at first saline, later sweetish, and then acrid and bitter."<ref name="Coblentz1899">{{cite book|author=Virgil Coblentz|title=The Newer Remedies ...: A Reference Book for Physicians, Pharmacists, and Students|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TvBkrWGGFSYC&pg=PA86|year=1899|publisher=P. Blakiston's son & Company|pages=86–}}</ref>
