{{notability|date=November 2014}} '''“Mowgli syndrome”''' is a term used by [[Wendy Doniger O'Flaherty|Wendy Doniger O’Flaherty]] in her 1995 book ''Other Peoples’ Myths: The Cave of Echoes'' to describe mythological figures who succeed in bridging the animal and human worlds to become one with nature, a human animal, only to become trapped between the two worlds, not completely animal yet not entirely human.<ref>{{Cite book | first = Wendy | last = Doniger O'Flaherty | authorlink = Wendy Doniger O'Flaherty | title = Other Peoples' Myths: The Cave of Echoes | publisher = University of Chicago Press | year = 1995 | location = Chicago | pages = 75–96 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=nzIGfC7vevoC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA78#v=onepage&q=&f=false | isbn = 0226618579 }}</ref>
It is also a rarely used descriptive term for so-called [[feral child]]ren; “Mowgli syndrome” is not a recognized psychological or physiological malady. The term originates from the character [[Mowgli]], a fictional feral child from [[Rudyard Kipling]]’s ''[[The Jungle Book]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/893675823|title=The Medical Lives of History's Famous People|last=James|first=Maloney, William|publisher=|year=2014|isbn=9781608059362|location=|pages=136-139|oclc=893675823|quote=|via=http://ebooks.benthamscience.com/}}</ref>
